    <article>
        <section xml:id="ps02">
            <title>Problem Set 02</title>
            <subtitle>Essential Calculus, Early Transcendentals: Sections 6.1 and 6.2</subtitle>

            <exercises>
                <exercise xml:id="ps02-01">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Evaluate the indefinite integral <m>\int x^2 e^{2x} \, dx</m>. You must show all steps of the integration by parts process.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We use integration by parts, with the LIATE rule suggesting we choose <m>u</m> as the polynomial term. We will need to apply the process twice.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            For the first iteration, let:
                            <me>
                                u = x^2 \quad \text{and} \quad dv = e^{2x} \, dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                du = 2x \, dx \quad \text{and} \quad v = \frac{1}{2}e^{2x}
                            </me>
                            Using the formula <m>\int u \, dv = uv - \int v \, du</m>, we get:
                            <me>
                                \int x^2 e^{2x} \, dx = x^2 \left( \frac{1}{2}e^{2x} \right) - \int \frac{1}{2}e^{2x} (2x) \, dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{2}x^2 e^{2x} - \int x e^{2x} \, dx
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We now apply integration by parts again to the new integral <m>\int x e^{2x} \, dx</m>. Let:
                            <me>
                                u = x \quad \text{and} \quad dv = e^{2x} \, dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                du = dx \quad \text{and} \quad v = \frac{1}{2}e^{2x}
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                \int x e^{2x} \, dx = x \left( \frac{1}{2}e^{2x} \right) - \int \frac{1}{2}e^{2x} \, dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{2}x e^{2x} - \frac{1}{4}e^{2x} + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Substituting this result back into our first equation, we get the final answer:
                            <me>
                                \int x^2 e^{2x} \, dx = \frac{1}{2}x^2 e^{2x} - \left( \frac{1}{2}x e^{2x} - \frac{1}{4}e^{2x} \right) + C
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{2}x^2 e^{2x} - \frac{1}{2}x e^{2x} + \frac{1}{4}e^{2x} + C
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{4}e^{2x}(2x^2 - 2x + 1) + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>

                <exercise xml:id="ps02-02">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Evaluate the definite integral <m>\int_1^e \ln(x^4) \, dx</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            First, we can simplify the integrand using a logarithm property: <m>\ln(x^4) = 4\ln(x)</m>.
                            <me>
                                \int_1^e 4\ln(x) \, dx = 4 \int_1^e \ln(x) \, dx
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            To evaluate <m>\int \ln(x) \, dx</m>, we use integration by parts with a clever choice of <m>dv</m>. Let:
                            <me>
                                u = \ln(x) \quad \text{and} \quad dv = dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                du = \frac{1}{x} \, dx \quad \text{and} \quad v = x
                            </me>
                            Applying the integration by parts formula:
                            <me>
                                \int \ln(x) \, dx = x\ln(x) - \int x \left( \frac{1}{x} \right) \, dx = x\ln(x) - \int 1 \, dx = x\ln(x) - x + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now we evaluate the definite integral using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus:
                            <me>
                                4 \int_1^e \ln(x) \, dx = 4 \left[ x\ln(x) - x \right]_1^e
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = 4 \left( (e\ln(e) - e) - (1\ln(1) - 1) \right)
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = 4 \left( (e(1) - e) - (1(0) - 1) \right) = 4(0 - (-1)) = 4
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The value of the integral is <m>4</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>

                <exercise xml:id="ps02-03">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            A particle moves along a straight line with velocity <m>v(t) = t \sin(2t)</m> meters per second. Find the displacement of the particle over the interval <m>[0, \frac{\pi}{2}]</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The displacement is the definite integral of the velocity function over the given interval. We need to evaluate <m>\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} t \sin(2t) \, dt</m>.
                            We will use integration by parts. Let:
                            <me>
                                u = t \quad \text{and} \quad dv = \sin(2t) \, dt
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                du = dt \quad \text{and} \quad v = -\frac{1}{2}\cos(2t)
                            </me>
                            Applying the formula for definite integrals:
                            <me>
                                \int_a^b u \, dv = [uv]_a^b - \int_a^b v \, du
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} t \sin(2t) \, dt = \left[ t \left( -\frac{1}{2}\cos(2t) \right) \right]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} - \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \left( -\frac{1}{2}\cos(2t) \right) \, dt
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \left[ -\frac{1}{2}t\cos(2t) \right]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} + \frac{1}{2} \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cos(2t) \, dt
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now we evaluate each part:
                            <me>
                                \left[ -\frac{1}{2}t\cos(2t) \right]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} = \left( -\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\cos\left(2\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\right) \right) - \left( -\frac{1}{2}(0)\cos(2(0)) \right)
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \left( -\frac{\pi}{4}\cos(\pi) \right) - 0 = -\frac{\pi}{4}(-1) = \frac{\pi}{4}
                            </me>
                            And the remaining integral:
                            <me>
                                \frac{1}{2} \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cos(2t) \, dt = \frac{1}{2} \left[ \frac{1}{2}\sin(2t) \right]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} = \frac{1}{4} \left( \sin\left(2\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\right) - \sin(2(0)) \right)
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{4}(\sin(\pi) - \sin(0)) = \frac{1}{4}(0-0) = 0
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Combining the results, the displacement is <m>\frac{\pi}{4} + 0 = \frac{\pi}{4}</m> meters.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>

                <exercise xml:id="ps02-04">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Evaluate the indefinite integral <m>\int \sin^3(x) \cos^4(x) \, dx</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This is a trigonometric integral with odd powers of sine. We can split off one factor of <m>\sin(x)</m> and use the identity <m>\sin^2(x) = 1 - \cos^2(x)</m>.
                            <me>
                                \int \sin^3(x) \cos^4(x) \, dx = \int \sin^2(x) \cos^4(x) \sin(x) \, dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \int (1 - \cos^2(x)) \cos^4(x) \sin(x) \, dx
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now we use the substitution <m>u = \cos(x)</m>, so <m>du = -\sin(x) \, dx</m> or <m>-du = \sin(x) \, dx</m>.
                            <me>
                                = \int (1 - u^2) u^4 (-du) = \int (u^2 - 1) u^4 \, du
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \int (u^6 - u^4) \, du
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Integrating with respect to <m>u</m>:
                            <me>
                                = \frac{u^7}{7} - \frac{u^5}{5} + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Substituting back <m>u = \cos(x)</m>:
                            <me>
                                = \frac{\cos^7(x)}{7} - \frac{\cos^5(x)}{5} + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>

                <exercise xml:id="ps02-05">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Evaluate the indefinite integral <m>\int \tan^3(x) \sec(x) \, dx</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            For this trigonometric integral, we can split off a factor of <m>\sec(x)\tan(x)</m> and use the identity <m>\tan^2(x) = \sec^2(x) - 1</m>.
                            <me>
                                \int \tan^3(x) \sec(x) \, dx = \int \tan^2(x) (\sec(x)\tan(x)) \, dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \int (\sec^2(x) - 1) (\sec(x)\tan(x)) \, dx
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now we use the substitution <m>u = \sec(x)</m>, so <m>du = \sec(x)\tan(x) \, dx</m>.
                            <me>
                                = \int (u^2 - 1) \, du
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Integrating with respect to <m>u</m>:
                            <me>
                                = \frac{u^3}{3} - u + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Substituting back <m>u = \sec(x)</m>:
                            <me>
                                = \frac{\sec^3(x)}{3} - \sec(x) + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>
                
                <exercise xml:id="ps02-06">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Evaluate the indefinite integral <m>\int \sin(5x)\cos(3x) \, dx</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This integral requires a product-to-sum identity. The relevant identity is <m>\sin(A)\cos(B) = \frac{1}{2}[\sin(A-B) + \sin(A+B)]</m>.
                            In our case, <m>A = 5x</m> and <m>B = 3x</m>.
                            <me>
                                \int \sin(5x)\cos(3x) \, dx = \int \frac{1}{2}[\sin(5x-3x) + \sin(5x+3x)] \, dx
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{2}\int [\sin(2x) + \sin(8x)] \, dx
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now we can integrate each term separately:
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{2} \left( \int \sin(2x) \, dx + \int \sin(8x) \, dx \right)
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                = \frac{1}{2} \left( -\frac{1}{2}\cos(2x) - \frac{1}{8}\cos(8x) \right) + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Distributing the <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, we get the final answer:
                            <me>
                                = -\frac{1}{4}\cos(2x) - \frac{1}{16}\cos(8x) + C
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>
            </exercises>
